-INTRODUCTION- (20 pts possible)¶

Scientific question: (5 pts)¶

Does a mutation in the the down syndrome cell adhesion molecule-like protein 1 homolog gene (DSCAML1), cause a similar hindrance in lamina-specific synaptic connections in the retina for humans and mice?

Background on scientific question: (5 pts)¶

In different human chromosomes, there are different neuronal cell adhesion molecules. There is DSCAM which is on chromosome 21 and there is DSCAML1 on chromosome 11. This molecule works to repell cells from eachtoher after attaching. I am interested in how DSCAML1 in humans compares to the DSCAML1 of mice. In mice, DSCAML serves in neurodevelopmental functions all of which include synaptic adhesion, self avoidance and anxon guidance.

Scientific hypothesis: (5 pts)¶

If the DSCAML1 gene is mutant, then there will be retinal synaptic connection lost for humans and mice

Description of what analyses were done/ how the data was downloaded for the project: (5 pts)¶

A Pairwise sequence alignment was done to compare both human DSCAML1 to the mice DSCAML1. It was downloaded using the Bio packages for Align and Seq; and the information came from the NCBI database. A Blast search was then conducted using Bio.Blast to import NCBIWWW. This helped to run both the human and mouse sequence data. I then chose to create a Sequence logo so that I can visualize how each DSCAML looks and compare them to eachother. and Lastly, I wanted to get a visualization of what their structure looked like, so I chose to use PyPlot to take the image and code so I can find all of the intricate detils within each.

-LOADING IN PACKAGES- (15 pts possible)¶

Definition of each packages: (10 pts) <-- Shown below¶

Correctly loading all of the packages (5 pts) <-- Shown in code¶

~ Bio Package: ~¶

Biopython is a large collection of modules that contains multiple tools available to compute biological information.

Align (Bio sub-package):¶

Calling the "align" method places two sequences as arguments in order to identify regions of similarity.

ClustalwCommandline (Sub-sub package for align)¶

Note: Import using this code: from Bio.Align.Applications import ClustalwCommandline¶

This is used for carrying out automatic multiple alignment sequences; whether they be nucleotide or amino acid sequences

MafftCommandline (Sub-sub package for align)¶

Note: Import using this code: from Bio.Align.Applications import MafftCommandline¶

Command line wrapper for the multiple alignment program MAFFT.

AlignIO (Bio sub-package):¶

This package deals with files that contain one ore more sequence alignments

SeqIO (Bio sub-package):¶

This package (SeqIO) stands for Sequence Input/Output. It only deals with sequences as SeqRecord objects.

Seq (Bio sub-package):¶

This sub-package provides objects to represent sequences with alphabetical letters

~ Bio.Blast Package: ~¶

This is a package that has code that works with the inputs and outputs of the BLAST program

NCBIWWW (Bio.Blast sub-package):¶

This package code is used to use the NCBI BLAST server from the internet

~ Conda Package: ~¶

Conda is a source package that is available to multiple different systems. For example, I have a Mac OS system. It is also available for/ runs with Windows and Linux. It is able to install, upload & run packages.

-c bioconda mafft:¶

Bioconda is a channel for the conda package that has a repository of recipies that are available within GitHub.

~ Logomaker: ~¶

Note: Import using this code:¶

import logomaker as logomaker¶

pip install logomaker¶

Logomaker is a python package that generates customized logos for DNA, RNA or protein sequences

~ Numpy: ~¶

Note: Import using this code: import numpy as np¶

This is a python library that is utilized when one is working with large/ multi-dimensional arrays. Mathematical functions are used to operate these arrays/ matricies.

~ Pandas: ~¶

Note: Import using this code: import pandas as pd¶

This is a python package used for data analysis/ learning tasks. it is a manipulation tool that is built on the NumPy package that was explained in the above definiton.

~ Pyplot: ~¶

This ia an Application Programing Interface (API) for pythons matplotlib

Matplotlib.pyplot¶

Note: Import using this code: import matplotlib.pyplot as plt¶

Matplotlib is a library package for data visualization. We can create graphs, charts and plots. It is a numerical extension of NumPy.

~ String IO: ~¶

Note: Import using this code: from StringIO import StringIO¶

String IO is a module that is for an in-memory file-like object. When a String IO object is created, we are to pass the string to the constructor.

#Import proper package
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import logomaker as logomaker

#Load matrix?
crp_df = -logomaker.get_example_matrix('crp_energy_matrix',
                                        print_description=False)

#create logo object
crp_logo = logomaker.Logo(crp_df,
                          shade_below=.5,
                          fade_below=.5,
                          font_name='Arial Rounded MT Bold')

# style using Logo methods
crp_logo.style_spines(visible=False)
crp_logo.style_spines(spines=['left', 'bottom'], visible=True)
crp_logo.style_xticks(rotation=90, fmt='%d', anchor=0)

# style using Axes methods
crp_logo.ax.set_ylabel("$-\Delta \Delta G$ (kcal/mol)", labelpad=-1)
crp_logo.ax.xaxis.set_ticks_position('none')
crp_logo.ax.xaxis.set_tick_params(pad=-1)

# style and show figure
crp_logo.fig.show()

3D Protein measurements¶

The Process to get the PYMOL images for each DSCAML1 (both mouse and human) protein, I... 1) went to the reactome database

2) typed in DSCAML1

3) marked "Homo sapians" (human) and made sure to mark "Mus musculus" (mouse) to filter results to my wanted protein

4) For homo sapians, I clicked on the protein DSCAML1, scrolled to "external reference" and clicked the UniProt link. I then clicked "Structure" and downloaded the AlphaFold PDB. I changed this color to a raspberry red so that I could easily identify which was which (human vs mouse). Then I went to file, save image and placed it into my jupyter notebook files.

5) I did the same process for the Mus musculus. I made the color a cyanne blue.

two = residues[1]["CA"].get_coord()
